Chalco, China Shenhua, China Unicom: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-20T01:03:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-20/chalco-china-shenhua-china-unicom-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.7 percent to 23,163.38. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 0.5 percent to 12,935.59.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (2600 HK): China will raise
standards for rare-earth exporters and won’t approve new project
expansions in an effort to curb overcapacity, illegal mining and
sales, the government said yesterday. Aluminum Corp. of China
Ltd., the nation’s biggest producer of the metal known as Chalco,
rose 1.6 percent to HK$6.95.  China Shenhua Energy Co. (1088 HK): Mongolia will announce
in June the winning bid to develop a coal deposit with 1.2
billion tons, the Xinhua News Agency said. China Shenhua’s
parent is one of the six finalists. Shares of China Shenhua, a
unit of the country’s biggest coal producer, rose 1.4 percent to
HK$36.05.  China Unicom ( Hong Kong ) Ltd. (762 HK): The nation’s
second-biggest mobile-phone company said it added 1.82 million
new 3G service subscribers in April. The stock jumped 4.5
percent to HK$15.88.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  (5 HK):  Europe ’s largest bank by market
value sees a “quite high” chance to be a yuan clearing bank in
Hong Kong if rules allow, said  Peter Wong , the bank’s chief
executive officer for the Asia-Pacific region. HSBC fell 0.3
percent to HK$80.55.  Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corp. (981)  (981 HK):
China’s biggest chipmaker said first-quarter net income was
$10.2 million compared with $68.6 million in the fourth quarter
and a loss of $182 million in the same period last year. The
stock was unchanged at 78 Hong Kong cents.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): The world’s biggest
developer may start sales of as many as 120 apartments in its
Imperial Cullinan and i.UniQ developments in Hong Kong next week,
the Standard said, citing Amy Teo, the project sales manager.
The stock increased 2 percent to HK$121.20.  To contact the reporter on this story:
